{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488483"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/457"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.39,0.11,0.01,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41677"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26604"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41677"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents with a two week history of a swelling in his right groin. The swelling became noticeable after a recent episode of constipation. He has never had any similar swellings before. It does not move down into his testicle. He is otherwise well with no medical conditions, surgical history, or current medications. He does not smoke or drink alcohol. He enjoys going to the gym five times a week. On examination, the swelling is 6 cm diameter, firm, irreducible and situated immediately above the mid-point of the inguinal ligament.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features would suggest the most urgent need for surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Firmness over the swelling","Irreducibility of the swelling","Recent change in bowel habit","Recent onset of dysuria","Pain in the swelling"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E An incarcerated hernia is one that is irreducible on examination, and a strangulated hernia is one that has become ischaemic. Onset of constant \u003Cstrong\u003Epain\u003C/strong\u003E in a hernia suggests that the contents of the hernia have become ischaemic. Depending on the likely contents of a hernial sac, so will vary the urgency of surgical intervention. Strangulated small bowel in a groin hernia demands prompt surgical attention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrreducibility\u003C/strong\u003E, or an incarcerated hernia, is not an urgent need for surgical intervention. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Echanges in bowel habit\u003C/strong\u003E alone do not indicate a definitive need for surgical intervention. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Erecent onset dysuria\u003C/strong\u003E should prompt one to consider other differentials and diagnoses such as a sexually transmitted infection or urinary tract infection, it is not a reason to consider surgical intervention in a hernia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirmness over the swelling\u003C/strong\u003E is not a specific sign of incarceration or strangulation, and thus, does not mandate surgical intervention. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Strangulated hernias often present with persistent pain, and may require urgent surgical intervention if contents of the bowel are involved."],"references":["Fitzgibbons RJ, Forse RA. Groin Hernias in Adults N Engl J Med 2015;372:756-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26604"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26604"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-21T11:41:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-21T11:41:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41677"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing informati